2 Top 8800 Twitch Streamers

2.1 Q1: Problem Statement

Twitch.tv is a popular platform for video streaming. It is extremely popular with younger audiences since allows sharing live gameplay for others to watch and comment on in real time. Any person with a Twitch account can broadcast their games (as long as they have the right equipment); however, being a successful Twitch streamer is not only a matter of pride, it is also a good source of income. Popular Twitch streamers get in average $250 a month for every 100 subscribers in addition of ad revenue. Lately, due to the COVID-19 pandemic that forced many people to stay at home, Twitch.tv has massively increased in overall watch time and in popularity. For this reason, I decided to study a dataset that compiles the statistics of the top 8800 Twitch streamers from 6 months ago (I got the data on Kagle). My intention is to find a model to predict the popularity of a Twitch streamer which I define as this persons average number of viewers per stream.

# Loading in the data
twitch <- read.csv("TwitchDataSet.csv")
names(twitch)
##  [1] "profile.picture"  "top.count"        "screen.name"      "watch.time"      
##  [5] "stream.time"      "peak.viewers"     "average.viewers"  "followers"       
##  [9] "followers.gained" "views.gained"     "partnered"        "mature"          
## [13] "language"         "completa.name"    "first.category"   "second.category" 
## [17] "third.category"

The data collected has information on the top 8800 Twitch streamers. The top 8800 streamers from this dataset is defined solely on overall watch time a streamer has. With this information I hope to determine what are the most likely predictors of a streamers average viewers per stream. There are 17 pieces of data collected from the dataset. Some of the collected data is not that useful because it is specific to the observation. These include profile.picture, top.count, screen.name, and completa.name. These are the variables that are definitely not useful to regression. From the rest of the 13 variables, average.viewers is the response variable. This variable represents the average amount of viewers the streamer had per stream in a one year period from October 2019 - October 2020. Next I will explain all the potential predictors of the average.viewers (Every variable is calculated over the same one year period October 2019 - October 2020):

  • watch.time represents the total minutes spent watching a streamer from all viewers over the one year time period.
  • stream.time represents the total minutes a streamer streamed over the one year period.
  • peak.viewers represents the maximum number of viewers a streamer had during any stream over the one year period.
  • followers represents the amount of viewers who follow the streamer on their twitch account.
  • followers.gained represents the amount of followers a streamer gained over the one year period.
  • views.gained represents the number of individual views a streamer gained over the one year period.
  • partnered represents whether a streamer is partnered with a twitch or not.
  • mature represents whether a streamers content is made of mature audiences or not.
  • language represents the designated language of a streamer.
  • first.category represents the most streamed category(game or activity) of the streamer.
  • second.category represents the second most streamed category(game or activity) of the streamer.
  • third.category represents the third most streamed category(game or activity) of the streamer.


I believe that this data is suitable to assess the average viewers of the top streamers, but might not work for newer streamers without a big following because all the streamers I have data for will have significantly more viewers, followers, etc than many streamers on the platform.

2.2.1 Response variable: average.viewers

ggplot(twitch, aes(x=average.viewers)) + geom_histogram(fill="#3ea6f0", color="#1f4866", alpha=0.9 ) + ggtitle("Average number of viewers") + theme_minimal() + theme(plot.title = element_text(size=15))

boxplot(twitch$average.viewers, main="Average Viewers", horizontal=TRUE, xlab="count", col="darkolivegreen")

Based on the information provided from the histogram, boxplot and the summary, the average viewers is skewed to the left, meaning that very few streamers average a significant amount of viewers per stream. The highest average is 193645 per stream which is much higher than any other streamer in this dataset. The vast majority of streamers (50%) average between 175 and 949 viewers per stream. Based on the boxplot, there are a significant number of outliers which amount ot less than 25% of the total data. I believe this is due to a relatively small number of streamers drawing in most of the viewers to the platform.

2.2.2 Correlation between variables

# Correlation between variables
twitch.subset <- twitch[, c("average.viewers", "watch.time", "stream.time", "peak.viewers", "followers", "views.gained", "followers.gained" )]
corrplot(cor(twitch.subset),method="ellipse", type="lower",title="Correlation between variables",addCoef.col ="black",mar = c(0,0,1,0))


Looking at the correlation plots, almost every predictor has a positive correlation with average.viewers except stream.time. This makes sense because it is harder to hold a large consistent amount of viewers if you stream for long hours. Based on the correlation plot, it seems that peak.viewers is the most strongly correlated with average.viewers. Another important thing to note is that watch.time seems to be correlated with the other possible predictors, so there might be multicollinearity. peak.viewers might have a similar issue. followers and followers.gained are strongly correlated which makes sense, so I should be careful about that.

2.3 Q3: Simple Linear Regression

Based on the correlation plots, peak.viewers has the highest correlation with average.viewers, so I chose that predictor for the simple regression model.

model1 <- lm(average.viewers ~ peak.viewers, data=twitch)

  geom_point(shape=18, color="blue4") +
  ggtitle("Average viewers on Twitch vs Peak viewers on Twitch") +
  xlab("Number of viewers at a streamer's peak") +
  ylab("Number of Average Viewers") +
  geom_smooth(method=lm, color="darkred", fill="salmon")


The scatterplot, shows a positive linear relationship between average viewers and peak viewers, however, the variance seems to increase as the peak viewers increases. Additionally, there seem to be quite a few outliers in the data that could influence the regression line. I dont believe that a transformation is necessary for this model.

The linear equation from the regression model is: \[\widehat{AverageViewers} = 37.29 + 0.001275(PeakViewers)\]


37.29 represents the amount of average viewers you would have if you had a peak viewership of 0 viewers. This does not make sense in reality because if no one ever watched your stream, you would not have an average viewership that high. No one in the dataset has a peak viewership that is close to 0 either way.

0.001275 represents how much your average viewers would increase if your peak viewership was one viewer higher.

The r-squared value from this mode is 0.34. This is not very high, but a t value of 67.87 for a hypothesis test of
\(H_0: b1 = 0\) and \(H_1: b1 \ne 0\), indicates that this model is better than no model at all. The low r-squared value is likely due to the outliers that exist in the data and increase in variance as peak viewers increases.

2.3.1 Model assessment


2.3.1.1 Linearity

# Residual plot
ols_plot_resid_fit(model1)


Based on this residual plot, there does not seem to be an obvious pattern that would suggest that the data is not linear, so the linear assumption is met.

2.3.1.2 Normality

# create QQ plot of residuals
ols_plot_resid_qq(model1)

# create a histogram of residuals
ols_plot_resid_hist(model1)


Looking at the QQ-Norm plot, it seems like the data points at the end of the model deviate from normal. Thus, the normal condition is not met.
I should mention that the histogram of the residuals does not provide a good sense of the normality of the model. Also, I was unable to run the Wilks-Shapiro test because it has a limit on the number of observations it can process (at most 5000 observations).

2.3.2 Independence

The correlation plot showed that some possible predictor variables could be corrrelated. watch.time is a predictor that has a decently high correlation with peak.viewers, so the predictor is likely not independent. Thus, the independent condition is not met.

2.3.2.1 Equal Variance

# Breusch-Pagan Test
bptest(model1)
## 
##  studentized Breusch-Pagan test
## 
## data:  model1
## BP = 482.15, df = 1, p-value < 2.2e-16


Based on the fact the at the p-value for the Breusch-Pagan Test is low, the equal variance condition is not met. You can also see this on the residual plot because the variance gets larger as it continues.

2.3.2.2 Outliers

ols_plot_cooksd_bar(model1)


Looking at the cooks distance for the data points, there is one point that is very clearly an outlier compared to the others(data point 1070). There are 4 data points that have a Cooks distance notably more than the others. 

ols_plot_resid_lev(model1)


Most of the data set is either normal or has high leverage, there are a few points out of the 8800 data points that are influential points. Once again 1070 shows up as an influential point. Additionally point 4227 is a notable influential point.

newmodel <- lm(average.viewers ~ watch.time + stream.time + peak.viewers + followers + views.gained + followers.gained, data=twitch)

Compared to the simple linear model, this model has very influential points like point 1070 and 4227, but they do not seem to be as influential as they were in the other model.

2.4.2 Comparing Multiple Regression Model vs Simple Model

I will now compare the models using an F-test at 1% significance.

\(H_0: b2 = b3 = b4 = b5 = b6 = 0\) (All predictors, except peak.viewers dont add anything to the model)
\(H_1: H_0\) is not true

anova(model1, newmodel)
Res.Df RSS Df Sum of Sq F Pr(>F)

8793 86101088951 5 8858852688 180.9405 0

Based on the F value of 180.94 which produces a p-value of 2.2e-16, we reject the null hypothesis and conclude that the multiple regression model, which includes six predictors, is better than the original model which only included peak.viewers as a predictor.

2.5 Q5: Hypothesis Testing

Using the superior model, I will test whether or not followers.gained adds anything significant to the model. I want to check this because it seems very similar to the predictor followers which could mean that there is potential that it does not matter in the model. I will test this hypothesis at 1% significance.

\(H_0: b6 = 0\)
\(H_1: b6 \ne 0\)

2.6 Q6: Summary and Reflection


As a result of my study of the Twitch data, I determined that the best model to predict a Twitch streamers average viewership is the one with six predictors: watch.time, stream.time, peak.viewers, followers, followers.gained, and views.gained.

One of the insights I gained from this study is the fact that stream.time correlates negatively with the average viewership. This makes sense because streaming longer hours makes it more difficult to maintain a higher average viewership.

Additionally, a high peak viewership contributes to a higher average over the whole year. Higher total number of followers and the number of followers gained during the year imply a larger fanbase which tends to contribute to having more average viewers. Intuitively, a high watch time and views gained contributes to a higher average viewership as well.

Some difficulties I had with this study came from my inability to meet the LINE assumptions. Despite this, I think that this model provides some good insight into a Twitch streamers average viewership.

I believe that this model could be improved in several ways. I think that it would interesting to include the language of the streamer in the model. Its difficult to implement in the model because there are 32 different languages from the top 8800 streamers. Furthermore, I think that looking at the model after removing the data points 1077 and 4227 would be beneficial because those points are very influential in the model and stand out from all the other points.

Finally, I think that there is an obvious difference between the super popular streamers in the dataset and the everyone else because there is a group of points that are considered outliers on the graph. I think separating the two groups and running a linear regression on them independently could be interesting.
